__d(function(e,t,n,o,i,s,a){i.exports=[{id:"exp-godot",title:"My experience with Godot",excerpt:"Helpful resources that can help you with developing cool games.",body:"Here are resources that I found really helpful in Game Development:\n- [Steering Behaviors](https://code.tutsplus.com/series/understanding-steering-behaviors--gamedev-12732): This clearly shows you how to implement different kinds of steering behaviors (e.g: Wandering, Seeking,...)\n\n- [How I recreate Balatro's effect in Godot](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Alwy-TH0WzE): This was the video which taught me how to use `Tween` in Godot. It's just a formula, you just have to copy them and paste everywhere.\n\n- [The SECRET FORMULA for juicy movements](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YBgCUQVDRkw): This video taught me how to use `Spring` physics formula to make smooth animation.\n\n- [How I animate UI easily in my game Lexispell](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aagPe4dvM2M): This video taught me how to use `Tween` in details.\n\n\nThis blog will be updated recently.\n\n---",date:"2026-06-05",tags:["Godot","Game Development"]},{id:"how-i-create-my-website",title:"How I create this portfolio website?",excerpt:"Using SKILLS and DESIGN.md to make website fast.",body:"# How I Built My Portfolio Website\n\n## Why I Built It\n\nThere are three core reasons I embarked on this project:\n\n* **Showcasing:** I wanted a dedicated space to display my work to friends and colleagues.\n* **Experimentation:** I wanted to stress-test the capabilities of modern coding agents using `SKILLS` and `DESIGN.md`.\n* **Innovation:** I enjoy exploring new developer workflows and pushing the limits of rapid prototyping.\n\nThe results proved that modern coding agents have become incredibly effective for structured, high-quality development.\n\n---\n\n## How to Do It\n\nTo replicate this workflow, you need two key resources: [Stitch-Skills](https://github.com/google-labs-code/stitch-skills) and [Cursor-DESIGN.md](https://getdesign.md/cursor/design-md).\n\n### 1. Integrate Stitch-Skills\n\n`Stitch-Skills` (from Google) enables agents to better interpret and follow `DESIGN.md` files. To set it up, create your project folder and run:\n\n```bash\nnpx skills add google-labs-code/stitch-skills\n\n```\n\n### 2. Implement the Design\n\n`Cursor-DESIGN.md` allows you to replicate the sleek aesthetic of the [Cursor](https://cursor.com/home) website. Add the design schema to your directory with:\n\n```bash\nnpx getdesign@latest add cursor\n\n```\n\n*Note: You can explore more design schemas at [awesome-design-md](https://github.com/voltagent/awesome-design-md).*\n\n---\n\n## Prerequisites\n\nTo make this work, you need a capable coding agent. While I used **OpenCode**, most modern agents will work.\n\nEnsure that during the `Stitch-Skills` installation, you correctly configure your agent's skill set. If you are using `OpenCode`, this integration is handled natively.\n\n---\n\n## What to Expect\n\nThis workflow is excellent for **high-fidelity prototyping**.\n\nThe generated website will look polished and professional, but it is currently best suited for \"one-shot\" generation. If you intend to add complex, dynamic features later, you will likely need to shift from agent-led generation to manual refinement. It is a fantastic way to turn an idea into a visual reality in minutes, rather than a long-term architectural solution.\n\n---",date:"2026-06-04",tags:["AI","SKILLS","DESIGN.md","Website","UI","UX"]}]},439,[]);
